{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} '''Alexander Anderson''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] [[Fellow of the Linnean Society of London|FLS]]}} (1748 in [[Aberdeen]], Scotland – 1811 on [[Saint Vincent (island)|St.&nbsp;Vincent Island, Caribbean]]) was a Scottish surgeon and botanist.
Anderson studied at [[Edinburgh University]]. Fellow Aberdonian [[William Forsyth (horticulturist)|William Forsyth]] briefly employed him at the [[Chelsea Physic Garden]] in London, prior to Anderson's emigration to New York in 1774, where he stayed with his brother John, a printer.<ref>{{cite book|last=Howard|first=Richard Alden|authorlink=Richard Alden Howard|title=The St.&nbsp;Vincent Botanical Garden – the early years|url=http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/476.pdf|year=1996}}</ref>
He was appointed in 1785 superintendent of the [[Botanic Gardens St. Vincent|government botanic garden]] at St.&nbsp;Vincent, where he showed much activity. He was a correspondent of [[Joseph Banks|Sir Joseph Banks]], through whom he contributed to the Royal Society in 1789 an account of a [[bitumen|bituminous]] lake on St.&nbsp;Vincent, which was afterwards published in the ''Philosophical Transactions'' for that year.
In January 1791 he was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]], proposed by [[Daniel Rutherford]], [[John Walker (naturalist)|John Walker]] and [[William Wright (botanist)|William Wright]].<ref name="Waterston">{{cite book |last1=Waterston |first1=Charles D |last2=Macmillan Shearer |first2=A |title=Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783–2002: Biographical Index |url=http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf |accessdate=8 February 2011 |volume=I |date=July 2006 |publisher=[[The Royal Society of Edinburgh]] |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-902198-84-5 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004113545/http://www.rse.org.uk/fellowship/fells_indexp1.pdf |archivedate=4 October 2006 }}</ref> In the same year he went into [[The Guianas|Guiana]] on a botanising expedition; the plants he obtained being sent to Banks, are now in the herbarium of the [[British Museum]].
The [[Society of Arts]] voted him a silver medal in 1798 for a paper upon the plants in the garden at St. Vincent. He contemplated the production of a flora of the Caribbean islands, some sheets of which he sent to Banks; but this project was never carried out. He resigned his post in July 1811, and died on 8 September in the same year (the Royal Society of Edinburgh gives his date of death as 10 May 1811).
Anderson was succeeded as superintendent by his friend, the surgeon [[William Lochhead]].
